story.title: The Puppeteer - Episode 4
story.storyDescription: When Catherine discovers a creepy old puppet in her room, everything she thought she knew about her life starts to unravel.

messages.text: Dad? Is that you?
The puppet sheds a small tear from his eye.
Any fear that Catherine‚Äôs harboring disappears.
Dad! It IS you!
Oh my god. I can‚Äôt believe it.
What happened to you?
There‚Äôs so much I want to ask you.
It‚Äôs going to take forever for us to talk using this book‚Ä¶
The puppet blinks to dry his tears.
That‚Äôs it!
I can ask you questions. What if you blink once for ‚Äúyes‚Äù and twice for ‚Äúno‚Äù?
The puppet blinks once in agreement.
Okay, um‚Ä¶what do I want to ask you first‚Ä¶
How is this possible?
The puppet stares blankly at Catherine.
Oh, shoot, sorry. That‚Äôs right. I can only ask yes or no questions.
Okay, let me think.
God, haha, this is so insane.
All right‚Ä¶are you okay? Are you in pain?
Two blinks ‚Äì no.
Good.
Are you still‚Ä¶alive? I mean, not alive-alive, but still‚Ä¶here‚Ä¶in some weird way?
The puppet blinks once.
Catherine feels a rush of relief coupled with confusion.
You didn‚Äôt die in the accident?
Two blinks.
But everyone in town saw your car.
It was‚Ä¶horrible.
And we all went to the funeral.
Catherine begins to feel dizzy as questions keep racing through her head.
She takes a seat on the bed to steady herself.
Did you get into a different kind of accident?
Two blinks.
Did someone‚Ä¶do this to you?
One blink.
Catherine feels tears well up in her own eyes.
I don‚Äôt understand.
How could someone turn a person into a puppet?
And why would they want to?
Everyone in our town loved you.
The puppet stares at Catherine blankly.
Right‚Ä¶I should probably keep asking questions while we have time. Maybe about what happened?
The puppet blinks once.
Um‚Ä¶so was it‚Ä¶was it someone from out of town? A stranger?
Two blinks.
What?! It was someone you knew?
One blink.
Who was it?
Was it someone I know?
The sound of stomping feet echoes through the house.
A moment later, Catherine can hear Aunt Agnes and Catherine‚Äôs mother catching their breath outside the door.
In a panic, Catherine whispers to the puppet, knowing her dad is trapped inside it.
Mom and Aunt Agnes are here.
They think you‚Äôre dangerous.
But this is great. Now I can stop them from hurting you.
Mom is going to be so relieved to know you‚Äôre alive!
The puppet blinks frantically.
What is it?
Don‚Äôt you want to see them?
Two blinks.
But‚Ä¶
Catherine gasps.
Are you afraid of Aunt Agnes?
One blink.
Catherine leaps up from the bed and exclaims‚Ä¶
I knew it!
I always said something was off about her!
All of those trinkets she wears‚Ä¶
And you two never got along.
She always used to complain about all the men in this family and I always thought it was because she was bitter‚Ä¶
But I never thought she was actually evil.
The puppet blinks frantically again, but Catherine is distracted by a knock on her bedroom door.
Catherine, I‚Äôm giving you one more chance to open this door before we break it down.
Shit!
I can‚Äôt let her hurt you again.
And with that, Catherine grabs the puppet and slithers out of her bedroom window.
As Catherine crouches down in the bushes outside of her bedroom window, she hears a loud crash.
Her mother and Agnes must have broken down the door to her bedroom.
She sits still as stone, listening in on their conversation.
The room is empty!
Where did she go?
She must have snuck out with the puppet.
How could you have let this happen, Marie?
This puts us at great risk.
We may still be okay.
There‚Äôs no way she could have recognized that it was her father. He‚Äôs been dead for years.
Don‚Äôt be so na√Øve. Even if she hasn‚Äôt realized yet, she‚Äôs alone with the puppet now.
They may be able to find a way to communicate, and then she‚Äôll find out for sure.
Who knows what kind of lies he‚Äôll tell her?
Let‚Äôs not worry about that yet.
Marie, I don‚Äôt understand how this happened. You must have made a mistake.
He shouldn‚Äôt be able to move.
If I did make a mistake, then it‚Äôs your fault too.
You‚Äôre the one who taught me--
Ugh, look at us! We‚Äôre still fighting about him.
You should have never married that horrible man.
He was too inquisitive for his own good.
I can‚Äôt disagree with you there.
I think Catherine has inherited some of that inquisitive nature as well.
It seems so. But it‚Äôs about time she started to learn. She‚Äôs of age now.
I know. I just want to make sure I teach her correctly.
She has great potential, you know.
She‚Äôs very smart and her wit is quick.
She could do great things.
Very smart, indeed.
So smart that you think she‚Äôs started to realize that she‚Äôs a witch?
Catherine leans closer to the window, straining to hear more.
The shift in her weight breaks the slim branch below her feet.
Someone‚Äôs outside the window!
Catherine‚Äôs mother and aunt rush towards the window, only to see Catherine sprinting towards the woods with the puppet clutched in her hand.
Stop her!
Thank god I keep one of these in here‚Ä¶
Catherine‚Äôs mother scurries to the corner of the bedroom and pries up a loose floorboard.
She pulls out a dusty old tome, peels apart its brittle pages, and drapes the ribbon bookmark across the open page.
This should do the trick.
Catherine‚Äôs mother returns to the window and yells an incantation in Catherine‚Äôs direction, which echoes across the yard.
Catherine‚Äôs legs immediately stiffen into planks.
But her momentum forces the top half of her body forward, and she lands face-first in the dirt.
